{{Infobox artist | name = Lindsey Pollard | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Victoria, British Columbia]], Canada | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]] | spouse = | field = [[Animation]] | training = | movement = | works = ''[[Camp Lazlo]]'', ''[[The Chain Letter]]'', ''[[Family Guy]]'', ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'', ''[[Summer Camp Island]]'' | patrons = | influenced by = | residence = [[Los Angeles, California]] | influenced = | awards = {{awd|Emmy Award|2007}} {{awd|Pulcinella Award|2007}} {{awd|Norman McLaren Award|1994|Grand Prize}} {{awd|Montreal World Film Festival|1994|Best Animation}} {{awd|Emily Award|2008|Recognition of Outstanding Achievement}} | elected = | website = | bgcolour = }} '''Lindsey Pollard''' is an [[animator]] from [[Victoria, British Columbia]], Canada, now residing in [[Los Angeles, California]]. Her work as an animation director on the children's [[Cartoon Network]] series ''[[Camp Lazlo]]'' garnered three [[Pulcinella Award|Pulcinella awards]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.awn.com/imagepicker/image/10873 | archive-url = https://archive.is/20130117121034/http://www.awn.com/imagepicker/image/10873 | dead-url = yes | archive-date = 2013-01-17 | title = The big winner in the Pulcinella Awards was frosh series, Camp Lazlo | accessdate = 2012-08-01 | year = 2005 | work = Animation World Network | quote = The big winner in the Pulcinella Awards was frosh series, Camp Lazlo, created by Joe Murray. The show was honored with best TV series, best series for children and best character for Lazlo. }}</ref> two Emmy nominations, and a 2007 Emmy win.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ecuad.ca/node/928 | title = lindsey pollard receives emmy award | accessdate = 2012-08-01 | year = 2012 | work = Emily Carr University of Art + Design | quote = Lindsey Pollard (94) received an Emmy from the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences at the 59th Annual Primetime Emmy Awards, September 8, 2007. Pollard was nominated in the category Outstanding Animated Program for her work on Where's Lazlo? (Camp Lazlo) on the Cartoon Network.}}</ref> In 1994, she received The Grand Prize [[Norman McLaren Award]] and won "Best Animation" in the [[Montreal World Film Festival]] for her student film ''[[The Chain Letter]]''. As a member of The [[Emily Carr Institute]] Alumni, she received The [[Emily Award]] in Recognition of Outstanding Achievement in 2008. Lindsey was an assistant director on ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'' and a timer on ''[[My Gym Partner's A Monkey]]'', ''[[The Simpsons]]'', ''[[Drawn Together]]'', ''[[The Fairly OddParents]]'', ''[[The Oblongs]]'', ''[[Baby Blues (US TV series)|Baby Blues]]'', ''[[The Cramp Twins]]'', and ''[[Mission Hill (TV series)|Mission Hill]]''. She is currently a retake director on the Emmy award winning hit series ''[[Family Guy]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ecuad.ca/about/news/78816 | title = lindsey pollard (94), director | accessdate = 2012-08-01 | year = 2012 | work = Emily Carr University of Art + Design | quote = Since graduating from Emily Carr in 1994, and moving to Los Angeles, CA, Lindsey has worked on a variety of animated primetime and children’s programs. For eight seasons, she was a timer for the television show, The Simpsons and also worked on the feature film, The Simpsons Movie as an assistant director. Her work as a director on the children’s television series Camp Lazlo for the Cartoon Network, garnered three Pulcinella awards and two Emmy nominations. In 2008, a second nomination for Lazlo, netted her first Emmy win. Lindsey currently works as the Retakes Director on the television show Family Guy and received an Emily Carr "Emily" Alumni Award in 2008.}}</ref>
